The paper deals with randomized algorithms in the context of distributed computing, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses complexity classes and the ability to decide languages, which are topics in Computational Complexity (cs.CC). Information Theory (cs.IT) is also relevant as the paper analyzes the success probability of randomized algorithms. The paper also mentions sets and hierarchies, which are topics in Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the power of randomization, which is a topic in Machine Learning (cs.LG).
